4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT REVISING CAMPAIGN FINANCE LAWS; PROVIDING THAT A
5 CANDIDATE MAY RECEIVE COMPENSATION OUT OF THE CANDIDATE'S PRIMARY CAMPAIGN
6 DEPOSITORY EQUAL TO THE WAGE THE CANDIDATE WOULD EARN IN THE OFFICE SOUGHT;
7 PROVIDING TIME LIMITATIONS FOR RECEIVING COMPENSATION; REQUIRING REPORTING; AND
8 AMENDING SECTION 13-1-101, MCA.”
9
10 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
11
12 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Candidate compensation -- when allowed. (1) While a candidate is
13 engaged in campaign activity, a candidate may receive compensation out of the candidate's primary campaign
14 depository, as provided in 13-37-205, in the amount equivalent to the wage that would be earned in the office
15 sought for nomination or election. A candidate for state legislature may use the daily rate provided for in 5-2-
16 301.
17 (2) A candidate is limited to receiving pay under subsection (1) for the following periods:
18 (a) from the filing deadline date for the office sought until the primary election day, if the candidate
19 is seeking nomination in a primary election;
20 (b) from the primary election day until the general election, for a candidate not subject to a primary
21 election or a candidate declared nominated in a primary election; and
22 (c) from the general election day until the candidate is sworn in to office, for a candidate declared
23 elected to office.
24 (3) When a candidate expends funds from the candidate's primary campaign depository to receive
25 compensation, each expenditure must be reported as required under this part.
26 (4) After the candidate's closing campaign report provided for in 13-37-228 is filed, the candidate
27 may not expend surplus campaign funds for the candidate's compensation, as provided in 13-37-240.
